00:35:05.880 --> 00:35:07.180
&gt;&gt; Adrienne Lundgren: Yeah.

00:35:07.180 --> 00:35:09.370
So with this particular
era of photography,

00:35:09.370 --> 00:35:12.700
they were really trying to
legitimize photography and kind

00:35:12.700 --> 00:35:16.550
of put it on the same level as
other types of art like drawing

00:35:16.550 --> 00:35:19.680
and painting; and one of the
ways that they did that was

00:35:19.680 --> 00:35:21.910
through the manipulation
of the print.

00:35:21.910 --> 00:35:24.780
So one of the processes
that allowed

00:35:24.780 --> 00:35:29.680
for this really varied
manipulation was called the

00:35:29.680 --> 00:35:30.980
platinum process.

00:35:30.980 --> 00:35:34.460
So almost not everything Day
made, but most everything

00:35:34.460 --> 00:35:38.430
that he printed in his career
was made using the platinum

00:35:38.430 --> 00:35:43.180
printing process and platinum
is basically a paper support

00:35:43.180 --> 00:35:47.580
and the image is actually
made with platinum metal

00:35:47.580 --> 00:35:50.830
that is deposited into
the fibers of that paper.

00:35:50.830 --> 00:35:56.140
So they're extremely
stable, if made correctly,

00:35:56.140 --> 00:35:58.600
and were called the
prints of processes these

00:35:58.600 --> 00:36:03.710
because it has this
incredible richness and kind

00:36:03.710 --> 00:36:05.250
of what we call the
dynamic range,

00:36:05.250 --> 00:36:09.970
the levels between the bright
white and the dark, dark.

00:36:09.970 --> 00:36:11.420
Yeah.

