00:36:53.270 --> 00:36:54.570
&gt;&gt; Adrienne Lundgren: Yeah.

00:36:54.570 --> 00:36:55.870
&gt;&gt; Jer Thorp: So can
you talk about, like,

00:36:55.870 --> 00:36:57.170
the actual techniques
that you're using to try

00:36:57.170 --> 00:36:58.870
to make sense of this
large collection of images?

00:36:58.870 --> 00:37:00.170
&gt;&gt; Adrienne Lundgren: Yeah.

00:37:00.170 --> 00:37:01.470
So I mean, one of the things

00:37:01.470 --> 00:37:04.000
that I'm using is just really
systematic looking, like,

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:05.930
understanding how
these processes work

00:37:05.930 --> 00:37:10.090
and really cataloging all
the different variations

00:37:10.090 --> 00:37:14.010
that an artist could
use in making out.

00:37:14.010 --> 00:37:17.240
So that might include just
like I said, the mounts,

00:37:17.240 --> 00:37:21.350
just cataloging systematically
the mounts, but also looking

00:37:21.350 --> 00:37:23.580
at elemental composition
of the image.

00:37:23.580 --> 00:37:27.260
So really looking at
how that image was made

00:37:27.260 --> 00:37:29.410
and you can't always
do that with your eye.

00:37:29.410 --> 00:37:32.630
So one of the techniques that
we use is x ray fluorescence

00:37:32.630 --> 00:37:37.040
spectroscopy where we actually
it's a non distractive technique

00:37:37.040 --> 00:37:42.120
and you point that x ray beam at
the image and it excites atoms

00:37:42.120 --> 00:37:46.380
and gives you a spectra of the
elements that are in that sheet

00:37:46.380 --> 00:37:49.680
of paper and if you take
that spectra and combine it

00:37:49.680 --> 00:37:50.980
with the knowledge

00:37:50.980 --> 00:37:54.060
of the processes you can
really determine what type

00:37:54.060 --> 00:37:55.460
of technique they were using.

00:37:55.460 --> 00:37:59.550
So in the first image that we
looked up with the dying slave

00:37:59.550 --> 00:38:04.240
of Thomas Langryl Harris, that
image it's a platinum print,

00:38:04.240 --> 00:38:07.640
so it contains platinum, but
it also contains a large peek

00:38:07.640 --> 00:38:11.550
for mercury, so we know that
it was mercury process platinum

00:38:11.550 --> 00:38:14.080
print, which gives
it this brown tone.

00:38:14.080 --> 00:38:17.800
So artists tended to use
certain techniques habitually

00:38:17.800 --> 00:38:20.000
through their career
and so you can start

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:22.170
to understanding how much
manipulation they're doing,

00:38:22.170 --> 00:38:25.240
when they transfer from
technique, one technique

00:38:25.240 --> 00:38:27.850
to another, and it
kind of help you date

00:38:27.850 --> 00:38:30.810
and at tribute images to them.

