&gt;&gt; Jer Thorp: In the 1950s the
mathematician and metrologist,

00:46:17.340 --> 00:46:20.880
Edward Lorenz was
thinking about the weather.

00:46:20.880 --> 00:46:23.990
Now, Lorenz was experimenting
with statistical forecasting,

00:46:23.990 --> 00:46:26.460
but he found that his
simulations didn't match the

00:46:26.460 --> 00:46:30.770
messy, wet, reality
of the real world.

00:46:30.770 --> 00:46:32.600
Weather, right?

00:46:32.600 --> 00:46:35.280
So Lorenz set up to
development a nonlinear model

00:46:35.280 --> 00:46:38.170
that would match the
unpredictability of the nature.

00:46:38.170 --> 00:46:41.030
In 1963 he published
a paper called,

00:46:41.030 --> 00:46:43.990
"The Thermostatic Nonperiodic
Flow" in the Journal

00:46:43.990 --> 00:46:47.080
of Atmospheric Sciences, which
laid down the foundations

00:46:47.080 --> 00:46:50.930
for an entire branch of
mathematics called Chaos Theory,

00:46:50.930 --> 00:46:53.370
chaos systems are being
and that they start off

00:46:53.370 --> 00:46:54.970
quite predictable.

00:46:54.970 --> 00:46:57.330
After a certain amount of time
though they Saturday to behave

00:46:57.330 --> 00:46:59.150
in a way which for
a lot of intents

00:46:59.150 --> 00:47:01.690
and purposes resembles
randomness,

00:47:01.690 --> 00:47:05.230
this is why weather forecasters
can only predict the weather ten

00:47:05.230 --> 00:47:06.530
days out.

00:47:06.530 --> 00:47:10.760
One of the things that
define the chaotic system is

00:47:10.760 --> 00:47:13.410
that it's particularly
sensitive to initial conditions.

00:47:13.410 --> 00:47:16.570
That is, the state of the system
when it starts has a huge effect

00:47:16.570 --> 00:47:19.080
on how it will behave
long into the future.

00:47:19.080 --> 00:47:21.960
This idea that these
extraordinary, elaborate,

00:47:21.960 --> 00:47:25.250
mathematical structures could be
to dependant on minute changes

00:47:25.250 --> 00:47:28.150
in their state, right at the
beginning eventually gave rise

00:47:28.150 --> 00:47:30.330
to a famous term
that Lorenz coined,

00:47:30.330 --> 00:47:33.140
"The Butterfly Effect"
Lorenz's model,

00:47:33.140 --> 00:47:36.000
particularly The Lorenz
Attractor is a set

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:38.230
of three symboled
differential equations,

00:47:38.230 --> 00:47:41.220
there are three constants
called Sigma, Rho and Beta

00:47:41.220 --> 00:47:43.690
which define those that
delicate initial conditions

00:47:43.690 --> 00:47:45.220
that we spoke about.

00:47:45.220 --> 00:47:47.070
By changing the values
of these numbers,

00:47:47.070 --> 00:47:50.400
the system can now put a vast
monastery on strange geometries,

00:47:50.400 --> 00:47:54.230
from tight spirals to messy
tangles of loops and curls.

00:47:54.230 --> 00:48:00.410
Set to a very particular set
of values, 28/10 and 8 over 3,

00:48:00.410 --> 00:48:02.360
the Lorenz Attractor
outputs a structure

00:48:02.360 --> 00:48:04.450
which anyone would
have to admit,

00:48:04.450 --> 00:48:06.880
looks an awful lot
like a butterfly.

00:48:06.880 --> 00:48:08.820
It's when we watch that
butterfly emerge though

00:48:08.820 --> 00:48:11.100
by setting the system
free to animate over time

00:48:11.100 --> 00:48:14.350
that we get a real sense of the
beauty of the Lorenz Attractor.

00:48:14.350 --> 00:48:17.520
We see how it lives through
long periods of regularity

00:48:17.520 --> 00:48:21.030
where we start to recognize
a pattern only to seemingly

00:48:21.030 --> 00:48:24.950
at random to switch
course or change direction.

